The lab 4ct cushion cut diamond ring delivers 4ct face-up presence and D-VVS1 quality at $7,412 — a price point that represents 91% savings versus the natural entry at $85,685. At 4ct, the lab-to-natural price ratio reaches its most extreme point in the cushion market.

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Diamond</th><th>Cert</th><th>Colour / Clarity</th><th>Cut</th><th>Price</th><th>Reviews</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884798?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">4.00ct Cushion Modified Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$7,412</strong></td><td>20 reviews</td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25222994?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">4.00ct Cushion Modified Lab</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>D / VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$7,412</strong></td><td>17 reviews</td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28002666?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">4.00ct Cushion Modified Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / IF</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$17,598</strong></td><td>14 reviews</td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917439?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">4.00ct Cushion Modified Lab</a></td><td>IGI</td><td>D / FL</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$17,598</strong></td><td>11 reviews</td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27421366?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3.96ct Cushion Modified Lab</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>D / FL</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$22,931</strong></td><td>8 reviews</td></tr></tbody></table>

**The GIA vs IGI choice at 4ct D-VVS1.** Both the IGI 4ct D-VVS1 and the GIA 4ct D-VVS1 are priced at $7,412 — an unusual parity. At this price point, GIA certification is the stronger choice: GIA's grading standards are more conservative, GIA lab-grown certification carries higher recognition among insurers and gemological professionals, and GIA documentation will hold more value for any future resale or insurance appraisal. The IGI D-VVS1 may grade what GIA would call VVS2 or VS1 — not an invisible difference at 4ct face-up. When price is equal, choose GIA.

**The D-IF and D-FL premium at 4ct lab.** IGI D-IF and D-FL are both priced at $17,598 — a $10,186 premium over D-VVS1. At 4ct in a cushion modified brilliant, IF and FL clarity provides zero visible benefit over VVS1. The crushed ice facet pattern scatters light in a way that makes VVS1 and IF visually identical in the face-up position. The $10,186 pays for the grade on the certificate, not for any quality the eye can perceive. For complete analysis of the certification question, see the [lab grown cushion cut diamond guide](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

> "The Pillow Premium at 4ct reaches a number that forces buyers to confront what they are actually paying for. At $85,685 for a natural 4ct GIA F-VS1 cushion versus $7,412 for a lab GIA D-VVS1 4ct cushion, the premium is not a few thousand dollars of preference — it is $78,273 of preference. That is a number that demands honest examination. Most buyers who arrive at 4ct natural cushion have already decided on natural before they see the price comparison. The Empty Tier and The Pillow Premium together represent the full cost of that decision at scale.
>
> For buyers who have made that decision consciously: you are buying one of the rarest retail diamond configurations available. Three stones in the world, in stock, right now. That rarity is real, even if it does not appear on the certificate." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

