## Metal Choice for a 4ct Cushion

Metal selection at 4ct has more visible consequence than at 2ct–3ct because the 10mm face-up area means the metal's colour reflection into the stone's pavilion is perceptible at normal viewing distances.

**Platinum or 18K white gold.** The correct metal choice for D-F colour lab cushions at 4ct. A GIA D-VVS1 lab cushion at 4ct in platinum or white gold reads as a colourless, bright stone with zero warmth — the metal's neutral reflection preserves the D colour's visual supremacy. At 4ct, D colour in white metal is genuinely visible as a quality marker in a way that is harder to perceive at 2ct. For the [GIA 4ct D-VVS1 lab cushion at $7,412](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25222994?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), platinum or white gold maximises the visible return on the D colour grade.

**Yellow gold.** At 4ct, yellow gold performs the same function it performs at 3ct: it neutralises G colour warmth and makes near-colourless stones appear colourless. The natural 4ct GIA F-VS1 at $85,685 is F colour, which is near-colourless and reads clean in yellow gold. Yellow gold at 4ct also creates a distinctly different aesthetic from white metal — the warm, vintage character of a 4ct cushion in 18K yellow gold is a specific, intentional aesthetic choice that reads as luxurious rather than understated.

**Rose gold.** Rose gold at 4ct creates a high-contrast setting where the center stone's white brilliance reads against the pink warmth of the metal. At 4ct face-up, the contrast is more pronounced than at smaller sizes. For D-F colour stones in rose gold, the contrast is maximally dramatic. For F colour (the natural 4ct entry): rose gold's warmth may accentuate any colour in F at 4ct face-up; platinum or yellow gold are safer choices. For lab D colour in rose gold: the D-white contrast against rose is visually striking and intentionally luxurious.

